<div class="about container container--narrow">
  <h1>About</h1>
  <p>{{ site.author.bio }}</p>
  <p>夜食 — <em>yashoku</em> — means a late-night meal. Not dinner. Not a snack. The specific thing you eat after the last train, under a tarpaulin, in a city that hasn't stopped moving. That is what this site is about.</p>
  <p>Japan's nocturnal food culture is unlike anywhere else on earth. The izakaya that only fills up after ten. The ramen cart that appears at midnight and vanishes by three. The conveyor-belt sushi counter where the last chefs are still cutting fish long after most restaurants have locked their doors. These are not consolation meals for people who missed dinner. They are the point.</p>
  <p>I've been eating this way across Japan for the better part of a decade — in the yakitori alleys under the Yamanote Line, at yatai in Fukuoka, in Sapporo in January when the temperature makes the miso taste different, in the kind of Osaka standing bar where the counter is barely wide enough for your elbows. The writing here is a record of that, as honestly as I can put it down.</p>
  <p>No sponsored content. No hotel recommendations. No ranking of the top ten ramen shops in any city, because those lists are always wrong and always six months out of date by the time you read them. Just places I have been, food I have eaten, and an attempt to say something true about why Japan feeds people the way it does.</p>
</div>
